text: Yes. So we are fortunate that we do have some capabilities in-house to develop strategies. I'd say, depending on the asset class, now I'm mostly responsible, like I said, for the strategic and the tactical allocation. As I told you, it's mostly in derivatives. So for us, our hurdle is, can we develop it in-house and it's cheaper than 2 and 20? What is the cost of this? Because that's part of the carry too. So if I'm paying 2 and 20 plus whatever the cost of these strategies are, the theta decay, that is my total cost. So if I can do that in-house for cheaper than that or substantially cheaper than that, then it makes a lot of sense. And that's how we look at it. Now, the equity side of the house is very different. To manage an active equity portfolio, even a passive equity portfolio would require a ton of people, a ton of execution traders, and it's just not worth it. And if we can go get it passively for three bips, that's what we'll do. So it's really a cost function type analysis. I think it also, also based on expertise and trust we have in the ability of the people that are managing it. So that's how we look at it. And like I said, most of the time, we just can't get over that 2 and 20 hurdle. That carry is just too much. As you know, hedging is a decaying asset. It's a lot of times not cheap. So if we can develop it in-house and do it for bips as opposed to 2 and 20, it certainly helps the conversations when we talk about the performance of our program.
